    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nOS: Ubuntu 22.04.1 LTS on WSL Windows 10\r\nNeovim version: 0.6.1, installed via apt\r\n\r\nWhen I run `nvim foo.py` or try to save an existing buffer as `:w foo.py`, depending on which version of Python is active, Neovim will crash with the error message:\r\n\r\n```\r\nnvim: ./src/unix/core.c:258: uv__finish_close: Assertion `handle->flags & UV_HANDLE_CLOSING' failed.\r\n```\r\n\r\n(this also has the side effect of sending some janky terminal escape sequences and screwing up my shell prompt, I have to restart the shell)\r\n\r\n**This happens with a fresh install of Neovim, with no config file or plugins.**\r\n\r\nI discovered that this only happens when certain versions of Python are found on the PATH. I use pyenv to manage Python versions. Example:\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ pyenv global 3.9.16\r\n$ python --version\r\nPython 3.9.16\r\n$ nvim foo.py # works\r\n$ pyenv global 3.10.1\r\n $ python --version\r\nPython 3.10.1\r\n$ nvim foo.py # crashes\r\n```\r\n\r\nIt works for Python 3.9.16 and 3.11.1, but not for any Python 3.10 version.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n- have the current version of python be 3.10.x\r\n- open `nvim foo.py`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n- neovim should not crash\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.6.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nidk\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu 22.04.1 LTS on WSL Windows 10\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nAlacritty\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nscreen\n\n### Installation\n\napt",
    "closed_at": "2023-02-14T23:48:51Z",
    "comment_data": [
